quran[9]{c,v,t,f}:
  25,12,"When it sees them from a distant place, they hear its raging and roaring."
  25,13,"And when they are cast, shackled, into a tight place therein, there they plead for demise."
  25,14,"“Do not call<sup>pl </sup>for one demise today, but call for many demises.”"
  25,15,"Say<sup>sg </sup>, “Is that better or the Garden of Eternity promised to the ones who were mindful<i>(of God) </i>? For them it has always been a repayment anda destiny."
  25,16,"They have therein whatever they desire, as they abide. That has always been your<sup>sg </sup>Lord’s promise,<i>(worthy) </i>to be requested."
  25,17,"And on the day when He{1}herdsthemand what they worship apart from Allah, then Hesays{2}, “Was it you<sup>pl </sup>who misguided these servants of Mine, or was it they who strayed from the way?”",1:[Qira’at: All except for Ibn Kathir, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Ya’qub read it as: “…when We herd them…”],2:[Qira’at: Ibn Amer read it as: “…then We say,”]
  25,18,"They said{1}, “Highly Exalted are You. We should not have taken any{2}masters apart from You. But you allowed them to enjoy, as well as their fathers, until they forgot the Reminder and became a ruined people.”",1:[Frequently the Qur’an addresses the events of the hereafter in past tense; this grammatical shift should be pondered by the reader.],2:[Qira’at: Abu Ja’far read it as: “We should not have been taken as masters…”]
  25,19,"Thus they{1}have certainly disbelieved you<sup>pl </sup>regarding what you say, so you{2}can neither avoid<i>(punishment) </i>nor get any support. And whoever of you commits injustice, We will make him taste a supreme punishment.",1:[The false masters.],2:[Qira’at: All except for Hafs read it as: “…so they can neither avoid (punishment)…”]
  25,20,"And never did We send any emissaries before you<sup>sg </sup>but they used to eat food and walk in the marketplaces. And We made some of you a means of trial for others—will you be patient? And your Lord has always been All-Seeing."
